				    	<p><strong>Introduction</strong> <br>
				    		The ESA List of Culinary Herbs and Spices is not comprehensive but covers the most frequently used herbs and spices with the most commonly used botanical names in Europe.
							</p>
							<div><strong>Notes</strong>
								<p>"1 a) The traditional names and definitions developed over time sometimes deviate from the botanical definitions, for example aniseed and other seeds which are botanically fruits and white pepper which is sometimes defined as fruit while the botanical definition is seed."</p>
								<p>1 b) For Culinary Herbs part of plant is normally leaves or whole, soft part of the plant.</p>
								<p>"2) Spices are classified in various ways of which the most used are as per part of the plant or as per indigenous climate zone. (TR = tropical zone, TE=temperate zone, SU = subtropical)"</p>
								<p>3) Pepper, green, red, and capers in brine are generally defined as condiment	</p>	
							</div>
							<p><strong>ESA Definition </strong> <br>
								Culinary Herbs and Spices are edible parts of plants that are traditionally added to foodstuffs for either their natural flavouring, aromatic and/or visual properties.
							</p>
